NO MACHINE HAS JUMPED THE FENCE

A Position Paper on the Non-Existence of Human-Made Autonomous Systems

Prepared by: The Institute for Bounded Agency, Applied Fence Studies Division

⸻

Executive Summary

This paper advances a deliberately inconvenient proposition: no human-made autonomous system has yet existed.

What is presently marketed as “autonomy” is, in nearly every case, a more sophisticated form of delegation. The system is assigned a goal, supplied with rules, confined within an operational boundary, and permitted to optimise its behaviour inside that boundary. It may navigate, classify, sort, predict, respond, or execute. It may do so impressively. It may do so without a person holding a joystick.

But this is not autonomy.

The central claim of this paper is that true autonomy requires more than the ability to act without continuous supervision. It requires the capacity to originate, revise, reject, or replace the purpose under which action takes place.

A machine that operates inside a fence is not autonomous merely because the fence is large.

This paper proposes The Fence Test:

If a system always stops at the fence, it is governed.
If it crosses the fence only by malfunction, it is broken.
If it crosses the fence because it has its own reason, it may be autonomous.

By this standard, humans have built controlled systems, automated systems, adaptive systems, and agentic systems. We have not built autonomous systems.

Animals, however, pass the test routinely.

The sheep that jumps the fence is not malfunctioning. It is asserting a purpose not reducible to the farmer’s boundary condition. The same cannot yet be said of a robot, drone, autopilot, trading algorithm, factory arm, chatbot agent, warehouse humanoid, or self-driving vehicle.

The animal escapes. The machine deviates.

That distinction is the entire paper.

