3. Taxonomy of Non-Autonomous Systems

The confusion arises because several lesser categories are routinely mistaken for autonomy.

3.1 Controlled Systems

A controlled system follows direct commands.

Examples include remote-controlled vehicles, industrial machinery, and manually operated tools.

These systems do not decide. They transmit human agency through mechanical or digital means.

They are not autonomous.

⸻

3.2 Automated Systems

An automated system performs a fixed process without continuous human intervention.

Examples include washing machines, elevators, assembly lines, irrigation timers, and basic autopilot routines.

Automation reduces labour. It does not create agency.

The system acts alone only in the thin sense that a falling stone falls alone.

It is not autonomous.

⸻

3.3 Adaptive Systems

An adaptive system modifies its behaviour in response to conditions.

Examples include thermostats, recommendation systems, routing algorithms, trading bots, and many machine-learning models.

These systems may appear flexible. They may update predictions, choose among alternatives, and improve performance. But they remain enclosed within externally defined objectives.

They adapt inside the fence.

They do not decide whether the fence ought to exist.

They are not autonomous.

⸻

3.4 Agentic Systems

An agentic system can plan across multiple steps toward an assigned goal.

Examples include robotic planners, software agents, large-language-model tool users, warehouse robots, and autonomous-vehicle stacks.

These systems may produce behaviour that appears purposeful. They may decompose tasks, handle obstacles, recover from minor failures, and select strategies.

But their purpose remains assigned.

An agentic system may ask:

How do I complete the task?

A truly autonomous system may ask:

Why is this my task?

No machine has yet crossed this boundary.

⸻

3.5 Autonomous Systems

A truly autonomous system can generate, revise, suspend, refuse, or replace its own governing purpose.

It is not merely free to choose between authorised routes. It can question the journey.

It is not merely free to optimise the assigned task. It can reject the assignment.

It is not merely free to recover from error. It can decide that the original instruction has become morally, physically, or contextually subordinate to a newly recognised priority.

This is the level at which autonomy begins.

By this standard, autonomy is not currently an engineering achievement. It is a biological fact observed in animals and claimed by humans with varying degrees of credibility.

