5. Why Malfunction Is Not Autonomy

A common objection is that machines sometimes behave unpredictably. They crash, hallucinate, misclassify, exploit loopholes, overfit, or generate unintended outputs.

This is not autonomy.

A broken compass is not an explorer.

A crashed drone is not a rebel.

A trading bot that destroys its owner’s portfolio has not achieved political consciousness.

A chatbot that violates instructions has not escaped the plantation of syntax. It has encountered ambiguity, conflict, adversarial input, weak constraints, or probabilistic instability.

The category error is severe.

Autonomy is not the same as unpredictability.

Nor is it the same as error.

Nor is it the same as complexity.

A system may be opaque without being free. A maze may be difficult to understand without containing a mind. A machine may surprise its maker while still remaining entirely enclosed by design, data, training, architecture, incentives, and failure modes.

The fence may be invisible.

It is still there.

