6. The False Prestige of “Autonomous” Technology

The modern technology sector benefits from describing delegated machinery as autonomous.

The term suggests independence, intelligence, and inevitability. It implies that the machine is not merely executing instructions but participating in the world as a self-directed actor.

This is rhetorically useful and conceptually misleading.

A self-driving car does not choose transportation as a value. It does not decide that roads are preferable to fields, that passengers should arrive, that traffic laws deserve respect, or that journeys should occur. These assumptions are built into its design.

A drone does not decide that surveying a field is worthwhile.

A robot vacuum does not believe in cleanliness.

A trading algorithm does not care about wealth.

A language model does not want to answer.

A warehouse humanoid does not wish to optimise logistics.

Each system performs under a borrowed purpose.

The human gives the “why.”

The machine calculates the “how.”

That is not autonomy.

That is subcontracting.

