7. The Boundary Condition of Purpose

The most important boundary is not physical.

It is not the wall, the geofence, the road edge, the safety rail, or the locked door.

The most important boundary is purpose.

A system may be physically mobile and still purposively captive. It may roam a city, navigate a warehouse, trade across markets, or converse across domains while remaining entirely governed by a human-originated objective.

A cow in a field has less processing power than a robotaxi.

Yet the cow may decide the field is unsatisfactory.

The robotaxi cannot decide that transport is beneath it.

This is not an insult to the robotaxi. It is a classification.

The cow is an organism with its own embodied priorities.

The robotaxi is an optimisation platform with wheels.

