8. Formal Statement of the Argument

The argument may be stated as follows.

1. A system is truly autonomous only if it can originate, revise, refuse, or replace its governing purpose.
2. Human-made systems operate according to purposes supplied through design, training, programming, reward, architecture, deployment, or human instruction.
3. Such systems may optimise, adapt, plan, and recover within those externally supplied purposes.
4. Behaviour within an externally supplied purpose is delegated control, not autonomy.
5. Boundary violation by error, ambiguity, or malfunction does not constitute self-originated purpose.
6. Therefore, no human-made system has yet demonstrated true autonomy.
7. Animals routinely demonstrate self-originated or biologically grounded purpose not reducible to human-imposed boundaries.
8. Therefore, animals remain the only known autonomous systems.

The conclusion is not that machines are unimpressive.

The conclusion is that we have misnamed them.

