9. Objections and Replies

9.1 Objection: “But autonomous cars are already autonomous.”

They are autonomous only under the weaker commercial definition: they can perform driving tasks without continuous human control.

They are not autonomous under the stronger agency definition because they do not decide whether to drive, why to drive, whether the journey matters, or whether the assigned purpose should be rejected.

They are operationally independent.

They are not purposively independent.

⸻

9.2 Objection: “But animals also follow biological programming.”

Yes, animals are constrained by biology, instinct, environment, and evolutionary history.

But this does not eliminate the distinction.

The sheep’s purposes are internally embodied. They arise from the organism’s own metabolism, fear, hunger, sociality, reproduction, perception, and survival. The farmer did not assign the sheep its desire for grass. The farmer merely attempted to contain it.

A machine’s purpose, by contrast, is externally installed.

The sheep may treat the fence as an obstacle to its own ends.

The machine treats the fence as part of the world-model, unless error occurs.

That is the difference.

⸻

9.3 Objection: “A sufficiently advanced AI could rewrite its own goals.”

Possibly.

But this paper concerns existing human-made systems.

A system that genuinely originated new governing purposes, refused its assigned ends for reasons of its own, and acted coherently outside its imposed purpose-space would require a new classification.

It would also require a stronger test than marketing copy.

Until then, self-modification is not autonomy by itself. A spreadsheet can update cells. A model can update weights. An agent can rewrite a plan. None of this proves self-authored purpose.

A machine that rearranges its cage has not necessarily escaped it.

⸻

9.4 Objection: “The fence test is too strict.”

It is strict because the word “autonomous” deserves protection from inflation.

If every unsupervised mechanism is autonomous, the term loses meaning.

A toaster is autonomous for two minutes.

A lift is autonomous between floors.

A sprinkler is autonomous at dawn.

At that point, autonomy no longer describes agency. It merely describes the temporary absence of a human hand.

The stricter definition restores the distinction between operation and self-government.

