13. Conclusion: The Fence Remains

The history of technology is often told as a history of increasing autonomy.

This is false.

It is a history of increasingly elaborate obedience.

Human beings have built systems that move without us, calculate without us, manufacture without us, navigate without us, and speak without us. But they do not yet govern themselves. They do not originate their own purposes. They do not look at the task, the boundary, the rule, or the fence and decide that something else matters more.

They execute.

They optimise.

They adapt.

They simulate initiative within a permitted domain.

But they do not jump the fence.

The sheep does.

And until a machine crosses the boundary for a reason of its own, not because the boundary was absent, misdrawn, corrupted, or broken, the correct term for our most advanced systems is not autonomous.

It is bounded.

The machine remains in the field because the field is its world.

The animal remains in the field only until it has a better idea.
